  m_Name: DialogNPCFort
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  Name: Guzeppi
  Icon: {fileID: -1465489678553493566, guid: bdf9b2df1b7e9ab48b44781ca0257510, type: 3}
  HasInteraction: 0
  interactionType: 2
  Greeting: Guzeppi (George 11Labs)
  Day1Dialog:
  - "I have seen a fortress fall before. It never happens in one dramatic moment.\nWe
    move supplies across the harbour at night\u2014small boats, weapons, a few Maltese
    men risking everything to keep this place breathing.\nI just worry about when
    the Ottomans notice the pattern.\nAll we can do now is wait for tomorrow and
    see whether secrecy survives a little longer."
  Day2FirstTimeDialog:
  - 'Fort St Elmo was never designed to triumph. Its purpose is delay, nothing more.

    Every
    hour spent holding this ground is an hour bought for Birgu and Senglea to prepare
    their walls.

    Men here speak of victory. They misunderstand their assignment.

    By
    tomorrow, more of them will recognise the cost hidden inside that bargain.'
  Day2MetBeforeDialog:
  - "Yesterday, we moved men and supplies across the harbour and prayed the Ottomans
    wouldn\u2019t notice.\nToday, the boats carried wounded instead \u2014 and two
    of them died before the trip.\nWe lost time, and that small delay turned living
    men into cargo.\nBy tomorrow, I\u2019m afraid we\u2019ll be shipping more bodies."
  Day3FirstTimeDialog:
  - "The Ottomans finally noticed our crossings. They struck at the boats during
    the night \u2014 steel in the water, men thrashing in the dark.\nSome tried swimming
    with daggers between their teeth, and from here the sea looked more like a grave
    than a route.\nMany drowned before anyone reached them.\nFrom this distance,
    the screams on both sides sounded identical."
  Day3MetBeforeDialog:
  - "Yesterday we worried about the pattern being exposed. Last night it was.\nThe
    small boats were hit mid-passage \u2014 close-quarters chaos, men swimming with
    blades in their mouths, trying to reach rowing hands before they slipped under.\nSome
    Ottomans died, yes \u2014 but more of ours drowned with no one watching.\nFrom
    up here, the screams carried across the water the same way, regardless of who
    was dying."
  Day4FirstTimeDialog:
  - "The bombardment fell into a rhythm today \u2014 we are being bombarded from
    every side.\nThat tells me command has shifted. Someone patient is directing
    the guns now.\nOur crossings are almost gone. The sea might as well be a wall
    now.\nBy tomorrow, anything we failed to reinforce will be punished, one angle
    at a time."
  Day4MetBeforeDialog:
  - 'Last night, we scraped out a small victory at sea and still pushed a few trips
    across the water.

    Not today. There are watch-guards and cannon on both
    sides of the harbour now.  Some say a new commander joined the Ottoman''s ranks. 
    At this point, our crossings are fantasy.'
  Day5FirstTimeDialog:
  - "You\u2019re here on a day when the walls aren\u2019t defending anything anymore
    \u2014 they\u2019re just marking where men used to stand.\nSome of the lads are
    praying that God will get them out of here alive.\nThe Grand Master wants this
    fort to hold until the last possible moment, and that means none of us will leave."
  Day5MetBeforeDialog:
  - "You stayed longer than most, but that doesn\u2019t change what\u2019s coming.\nI
    stopped doing numbers last night \u2014 there\u2019s nothing left to adjust.\nTomorrow
    isn\u2019t about tactics anymore. It\u2019s about whoever can walk away from
    what\u2019s left."
  Day1Audio: {fileID: 8300000, guid: b1c41876c48335840b5745d3ed8a572c, type: 3}
